Introduction¶

The Fruits-360 dataset is a large collection of images of multiple fruits, vegetables and nuts. With over 94,000 images, this dataset has been designed to help researchers and developers in fields like computer vision and machine learning.

It includes 141 different classes of produce, such as apples, bananas, tomatoes, and much more.

In this dataset, each image is carefully captured at a size of 100x100 pixels. The images are organized into a training set of 70,491 images and a test set of 23,619 images.

The images were filmed using a special setup that involved rotating the fruits in front of a camera to create a clear view of each item. This process, along with an algorithm to improve image quality, ensures that the fruits are shown in a consistent way.

I'm trying to solve the following problem: Build a model that will classify fruits, vegetables and nuts.

GitHub link https://github.com/ammarhameed/DTSA-5511

Dataset link https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/moltean/fruits/data

def load_data(directory):
    data = []
    for class_name in os.listdir(directory):
        class_dir = os.path.join(directory, class_name)
        if os.path.isdir(class_dir):
            for filename in os.listdir(class_dir):
                if filename.endswith('.jpg'):
                    data.append({
                        'filename': filename,
                        'class': class_name
                    })
    return pd.DataFrame(data)

First CNN Model¶

In [16]:
def create_cnn_model():
    model = Sequential()
    
    model.add(Input(shape=(100, 100, 3)))
    
    # Conv 1
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    
    # Conv 2
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    
    # Conv 3
    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    
    # Flatten
    model.add(Flatten())
    
    # FC Layer
    model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))  
    model.add(Dense(141, activation='softmax')) 

    return model

model = create_cnn_model()

model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

history = model.fit(
    train_generator,
    validation_data=validation_generator,
    epochs=2,
    steps_per_epoch=train_generator.samples // train_generator.batch_size,
    validation_steps=validation_generator.samples // validation_generator.batch_size
)

Second CNN Model - A bit more complex model¶

In [29]:
def create_complex_cnn_model():
    model = Sequential()
    
    model.add(Input(shape=(100, 100, 3)))
    
    # Conv 1
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    # Conv 2
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    # Conv 3
    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    # Conv 4
    model.add(Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    # Global Average Pooling layer
    model.add(GlobalAveragePooling2D())

    # Fully Connected Layer
    model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))  
    model.add(Dense(141, activation='softmax')) 

    return model

model = create_complex_cnn_model()

model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

history = model.fit(
    train_generator,
    validation_data=validation_generator,
    epochs=2,
    steps_per_epoch=train_generator.samples // train_generator.batch_size,
    validation_steps=validation_generator.samples // validation_generator.batch_size
)

Fine tune hyper parameters¶

In [35]:
def create_complex_cnn_model():
    model = Sequential()

    model.add(Input(shape=(100, 100, 3)))
    
    # Conv 1
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    # Conv 2
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    # Conv 3
    model.add(Conv2D(128, (4, 4), activation='relu')) # <-- Fine tuned this to (4, 4) instead of (3,3)
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    # Conv 4
    model.add(Conv2D(256, (5, 5), activation='relu')) # <-- Fine tuned this to (5, 5) instead of (3,3)
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    # Global Average Pooling layer
    model.add(GlobalAveragePooling2D())

    # FC Layer
    model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))  
    model.add(Dense(141, activation='softmax')) 

    return model

model = create_complex_cnn_model()

model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

history = model.fit(
    train_generator,
    validation_data=validation_generator,
    epochs=4,# <-- Fine tuned this to 4 epochs
    steps_per_epoch=train_generator.samples // train_generator.batch_size,
    validation_steps=validation_generator.samples // validation_generator.batch_size
)

Predict some images!¶

And finally I will be picking up some images and will predict their labels

In [24]:
dataset_path = 'fruits/fruits-360_dataset_100x100/fruits-360/Training'

class_names = os.listdir(dataset_path)
class_names.sort()  

all_images = []
for class_name in class_names:
    class_path = os.path.join(dataset_path, class_name)
    images = os.listdir(class_path)
    for img in images:
        all_images.append((os.path.join(class_path, img), class_name))

random_images = random.sample(all_images, 10)

predictions = []
original_classes = []

for img_path, original_class in random_images:
    img = image.load_img(img_path, target_size=(100, 100))
    img_array = image.img_to_array(img) / 255.0   
    img_array = np.expand_dims(img_array, axis=0) 
    
    prediction = model.predict(img_array)
    predicted_class = np.argmax(prediction, axis=1)[0]
    
    predictions.append(predicted_class)
    original_classes.append(original_class)

for i in range(len(predictions)): 
    print(f"Original Class: {original_classes[i]}, Predicted Class: {class_names[predictions[i]]}")

Summary¶

Summary and closing thoughts

In this project, I worked on the Fruits-360 dataset, a comprehensive collection of over 94,000 images of various fruits, vegetables, and nuts, designed to facilitate research in computer vision and machine learning. The dataset has 141 distinct classes and it's divided into a training set of 70,491 images and a test set of 23,619 images.

  • EDA

    I performed exploratory data analysis (EDA) on the dataset, which included distribution of classes and visualize the images.

  • Model Development

    I built and evaluated three convolutional neural network (CNN) models, along with one transfer learning model, to classify the different fruites in the dataset.

Basic CNN Model:

Created a straightforward CNN architecture with three convolutional layers, each followed by max pooling and ended with a fully connected layer. The model was trained for 2 epochs.

Complex CNN Model:

Then I developed a more complex CNN that uses batch normalization and an additional convolutional block, which enhanced the model’s ability to learn from the data.

Fine-Tuned CNN Model:

Then I started fine tuning the complex CNN model by adjusting hyperparameters, which included changing some of the kernel sizes in the convolutional blocks, and I increased the training epochs to 4.

Transfer Learning with MobileNetV2:

Transfer Learning

And finally I have Leveraged transfer learning by utilizing the MobileNetV2 architecture as a base model, freezed its wegihts, and added custom layers for classification part. This model was also trained for 2 epochs.

Future work and enhancements

Finally I'd like to close this section by what can be done to enhance the work I've done, this includes:
- Add much more complex model and much simpler models and compare them for the best results
- Fine tune more hyper parameters
- Utilize bigger and fancier models for transfer learning
